Preheat your #oven to 220°C. Chop the @sweet potato{1} into small 2cm chunks
(no need to peel), place them on a #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season
with a @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}, then toss to coat. Roast in on the
top shelf of your #oven for ~{10%minutes}. While the sweet potato cooks, halve
the @red pepper{1}, remove the core and seeds and thinly slice. Halve, peel
and thinly slice the @onion{1} into half moon shapes. Peel and grate the
@garlic{2%cloves}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

After the sweet potato has been in the #oven for ~{10%minutes}, add the pepper
to the #baking tray{}, toss to mingle with the sweet potato and oil and pop
back in to roast until they are both soft and golden, another ~{15%minutes}.
Once cooked, remove from the #oven and set aside.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once
hot, add the onion and cook until soft, stirring occasionally, ~{5%minutes}.
Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}. Boil the #kettle{}.

Stir the @tomato puree{30%g}, @chermoula spice mix{1} and garlic into the
onions. Cook for ~{1%minute}, stirring constantly, then pour in the
@Water{}(for the tagine) and add the @honey{15%g}, @raisins{40%g},
@chickpeas{1%400g can} and half the @vegetable stock powder{1}. Stir
everything together and gently bring to the boil, then simmer until the
mixture has reduced and thickened, about ~{10%minutes}. Add the roasted
vegetables and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste.

Pour the @Water{300%ml}(for the couscous) into a large #saucepan{} on
medium-high heat, stir in the remaining @vegetable stock powder{1} and bring
back to the boil. Once boiling, remove from the heat, stir in the
@couscous{150%g}, then cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}. Leave for
~{10%minutes} to absorb the stock. Meanwhile, pick the @mint{1}(leaves picked
and finely chopped) from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks).

Once the tagine is ready, stir in the @Flora Original{10%g}. Then taste and
add @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it (and a splash of @water{} if
it's a bit thick). Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{} and stir in half the
mint. Taste and add salt and pepper if needed. Serve the couscous in #bowls{}
and top with the tagine, a dollop of @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g}, the
remaining mint and @flaked almonds{15%g}. Enjoy!

> Traditionally, tagines are slow cooked over a couple of hours, but this
> recipe brings all the flavour of an authentic tagine in no time at all.
> Served in the traditional way, with a warm couscous salad, the dish is finished
> off with a cooling dollop of yoghurt, crunchy flaked almonds and chopped
> fresh mint.